Text: ' The average albedo of the '
Reference: Earth ''
Text: ' is about 0.3.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Goode']
Text: ' This is far higher than for the ocean primarily because of the contribution of clouds.

Human activities have changed the albedo (via forest clearance and farming, for example) of various areas around the globe. However, quantification of this effect on the global scale is difficult.

The classic example of albedo effect is the snow-temperature '
Reference: feedback ''
Text: '. If a snow-covered area warms and the snow melts, the albedo decreases, more sunlight is absorbed, and the temperature tends to increase. The converse is true: if snow forms, a cooling cycle happens. The intensity of the albedo effect depends on the size of the change in albedo and the amount of '
Reference: insolation ''
Text: '; for this reason it can be potentially very large in the tropics.

'
Reference: File:Ceres 2003 2004 clear sky total sky albedo.png 'thumb|200px|left|2003-2004 mean annual clear sky and total sky albedo'
Text: '
The Earth's surface albedo is regularly estimated via '
Reference: Earth observation ''
Text: ' satellite sensors such as '
Reference: NASA ''
Text: ''s '
Reference: MODIS ''
Text: ' instruments on board the '
Reference: Terra (satellite) 'Terra'
Text: ' and '
Reference: Aqua (satellite) 'Aqua'
Text: ' satellites. As the total amount of reflected radiation cannot be directly measured by satellite, a '
Reference: mathematical model ''
Text: ' of the BRDF is used to translate a sample set of satellite reflectance measurements into estimates of '
Reference: directional-hemispherical reflectance ''
Text: ' and bi-hemispherical reflectance.  (e.&nbsp;g.,
.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'NASA']
Text: ')

The Earth's average surface temperature due to its albedo and the '
Reference: greenhouse effect ''
Text: ' is currently about 15&nbsp;°C. For the frozen (more reflective) planet the average temperature is below −40&nbsp;°C'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'washington']
Text: ' (If only all continents being completely covered by glaciers - the mean temperature is about 0&nbsp;°C'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'clim-past']
Text: '). The simulation for (more absorptive) aquaplanet shows the average temperature close to 27&nbsp;°C.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Smith Robin']
Text: '

'
Section [1] White-sky and black-sky albedo
Text: '
It has been shown that for many applications involving terrestrial albedo, the albedo at a particular solar '
Reference: Celestial coordinate system 'zenith angle'
Text: ' '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\theta_i}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' can reasonably be approximated by the proportionate sum of two terms: the directional-hemispherical reflectance at that solar zenith angle, '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\bar \alpha(\theta_i)}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ', and the bi-hemispherical reflectance, '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '\bar{ \bar \alpha}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' the proportion concerned being defined as the proportion of diffuse illumination '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{D}'
Close Tag: math
Text: '.

Albedo '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\alpha}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' can then be given as:

:'
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\alpha}= (1-D) \bar \alpha(\theta_i) + D \bar{ \bar \alpha}.'
Close Tag: math
Text: '

'
Reference: Directional-hemispherical reflectance ''
Text: ' is sometimes referred to as black-sky albedo and '
Reference: bi-hemispherical reflectance ''
Text: ' as white sky albedo. These terms are important because they allow the albedo to be calculated for any given illumination conditions from a knowledge of the intrinsic properties of the surface.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'BlueskyAlbedo']
Text: '

'
Section [0] Astronomical albedo
Text: '
The albedos of '
Reference: planet ''
Text: 's, '
Reference: natural satellites 'satellites'
Text: ' and '
Reference: asteroid ''
Text: 's can be used to infer much about their properties. The study of albedos, their dependence on wavelength, lighting angle ("phase angle"), and variation in time comprises a major part of the astronomical field of '
Reference: photometry (astronomy) 'photometry'
Text: '. For small and far objects that cannot be resolved by telescopes, much of what we know comes from the study of their albedos. For example, the absolute albedo can indicate the surface ice content of outer solar system objects, the variation of albedo with phase angle gives information about '
Reference: regolith ''
Text: ' properties, while unusually high radar albedo is indicative of high metallic content in '
Reference: asteroid ''
Text: 's.

'
Reference: Enceladus (moon) 'Enceladus'
Text: ', a moon of Saturn, has one of the highest known albedos of any body in the Solar system, with 99% of EM radiation reflected. Another notable high-albedo body is '
Reference: Eris (dwarf planet) 'Eris'
Text: ', with an albedo of 0.96
.'
