Two common albedos that are used in astronomy are the (V-band) '
Reference: geometric albedo ''
Text: ' (measuring brightness when illumination comes from directly behind the observer) and the '
Reference: Bond albedo ''
Text: ' (measuring total proportion of electromagnetic energy reflected). Their values can differ significantly, which is a common source of confusion.

In detailed studies, the directional reflectance properties of astronomical bodies are often expressed in terms of the five '
Reference: Hapke parameters ''
Text: ' which semi-empirically describe the variation of albedo with '
